CVE-2017-15906.summary: The process_open function in sftp-server.c in OpenSSH before 7.6 does not properly prevent write operations in readonly mode, which allows attackers to create zero-length files.

CVE-2014-1692.summary: The hash_buffer function in schnorr.c in OpenSSH through 6.4, when Makefile.inc is modified to enable the J-PAKE protocol, does not initialize certain data structures, which might allow remote attackers to cause a denial of service (memory corruption) or have unspecified other impact via vectors that trigger an error condition.

CVE-2010-5107.summary: The default configuration of OpenSSH through 6.1 enforces a fixed time limit between establishing a TCP connection and completing a login, which makes it easier for remote attackers to cause a denial of service (connection-slot exhaustion) by periodically making many new TCP connections.

CVE-2018-15473.summary: OpenSSH through 7.7 is prone to a user enumeration vulnerability due to not delaying bailout for an invalid authenticating user until after the packet containing the request has been fully parsed, related to auth2-gss.c, auth2-hostbased.c, and auth2-pubkey.c.

CVE-2016-10708.summary: sshd in OpenSSH before 7.4 allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service (NULL pointer dereference and daemon crash) via an out-of-sequence NEWKEYS message, as demonstrated by Honggfuzz, related to kex.c and packet.c.

CVE-2010-4478.summary: OpenSSH 5.6 and earlier, when J-PAKE is enabled, does not properly validate the public parameters in the J-PAKE protocol, which allows remote attackers to bypass the need for knowledge of the shared secret, and successfully authenticate, by sending crafted values in each round of the protocol, a related issue to CVE-2010-4252.

CVE-2016-0777.summary: The resend_bytes function in roaming_common.c in the client in OpenSSH 5.x, 6.x, and 7.x before 7.1p2 allows remote servers to obtain sensitive information from process memory by requesting transmission of an entire buffer, as demonstrated by reading a private key.

CVE-2011-4327.summary: ssh-keysign.c in ssh-keysign in OpenSSH before 5.8p2 on certain platforms executes ssh-rand-helper with unintended open file descriptors, which allows local users to obtain sensitive key information via the ptrace system call.

CVE-2010-4755.summary: The (1) remote_glob function in sftp-glob.c and the (2) process_put function in sftp.c in OpenSSH 5.8 and earlier, as used in FreeBSD 7.3 and 8.1, NetBSD 5.0.2, OpenBSD 4.7, and other products, allow remote authenticated users to cause a denial of service (CPU and memory consumption) via crafted glob expressions that do not match any pathnames, as demonstrated by glob expressions in SSH_FXP_STAT requests to an sftp daemon, a different vulnerability than CVE-2010-2632.

CVE-2012-0814.summary: The auth_parse_options function in auth-options.c in sshd in OpenSSH before 5.7 provides debug messages containing authorized_keys command options, which allows remote authenticated users to obtain potentially sensitive information by reading these messages, as demonstrated by the shared user account required by Gitolite.  NOTE: this can cross privilege boundaries because a user account may intentionally have no shell or filesystem access, and therefore may have no supported way to read an authorized_keys file in its own home directory.

Welcome to Mountain City, Tennessee
Thank You for Visiting the Official Website of Mountain City

Mountain City is located just a few miles from both the Virginia and North Carolina state lines. US Highway 421 connects Mountain City to Bristol, Virginia in the northwest direction and to Boone, North Carolina in the southeast. State Hwy 67, the winding road that travels alongside beautiful Watauga Lake, connects Mountain City to Elizabethton, Tennessee.

There is lots to explore in Mountain City and the surrounding area. There are antique shops, trails, lakes, a golf course and many more exciting things to do. We are proud of Mountain City small town charm. For more information about our town, give us a call or better yet, plan a road trip and see for yourself what our little town has to offer. You'll be glad you did.

Welcome to the Marion County Partnership

The Marion County Partnership for Economic Development (Partnership) is a nonprofit, public/private corporation formed in 1986 to address the need to advance the economic, industrial, business and civic welfare of Marion County.

The Partnership is funded by its members, which includes the county, cities, utilities, businesses, leaders and local professionals. The Partnership’s main purpose is to encourage growth of existing industry and businesses while giving all proper assistance to any new firms or individuals seeking to locate in Marion County. To this end, the Partnership works to promote the county as a single economic entity working in a complementary manner with local and regional economic development programs.

View the Partnership Brochure

By creating a system to allow lenders, government entities and local businesses and professionals to increase private investment in the communities, the Partnership works to:

  • Attract and retain quality jobs
  • Assist expansion and retention of existing companies
  • Solicit new business compatible with the assets and values of Marion County
  • Promote Marion County’s business images and
  • Enhance Marion County’s overall quality of life

Benton County Mayor
Brett Lashlee
 
 

Welcome to Benton County, Tennessee

>History of Benton County

Whether you are looking for a new place to call home, start a business, or set up an industry, Benton County has a wealth of resources to share. Our Community offers great schools, a large variety of tourism opportunities, quality healthcare, and we provide many cultural, civic and charitable opportunities. Benton County, with its close proximity to Interstate 40 and the Tennessee River, offers a vast amount of natural beauty and opportunities for growth. Our community airport is equipped with an automated fueling system and provides over 5,000 feet of runway. This airport is conveniently located near our Benton County Industrial Park and close to Highway 641 that connects to Interstate 40.

Benton County's Tennessee River allows residents and visitors alike to enjoy a variety of recreational activities such as hunting, fishing, boating, and sightseeing. The Benton County Veterans Park honors our veterans with a beautiful memorial for the public to visit at anytime. This park also offers a walking track with activities for softball, baseball, and soccer.

As Mayor, I am proud to represent the citizens of our county. My vision is to explore every opportunity available to make Benton County an even better place to live. We are proud of our county and welcome you for a visit. This will give you an opportunity to meet our great citizens and explore what our community has to offer.

If you have any questions or plan to visit our area please Email Benton County Government or call ( 731) 584-6011, and I will be glad to meet with you.

 

Benton County Government | 1 Courthouse Square | Camden, Tennessee | (731) 584-6011
